concern in supporting them economically, there is a social pressure not to divorce. Chadian women believe that their responsibilities as wives and mothers will be much harder to perform if their husbands are not around. Obviously, this is tied to the social restrictions placed on women.

The most common way to resolve these conflicts is through reconciliation,12 which is led by the brides father or her husband. However, the chances of this reconciliation are higher when the husband had been absent, beating during reconciliation.13 We suggest this is because spouses become less likely to reconcile if the husband is absent. In addition, stopping a husband from beating his wife is much easier during reconciliation for many reasons that women are more likely to express their needs. However, this does not take into consideration all of these factors, and our results could have a simple explanation, for instance, alcoholism that may control increased violence.
